article.headline: Creighton 57, Wichita State 55
article.story: OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Anthony Tolliver scored 20 points, including the winning shot at the buzzer, to help Creighton rally from 19 down to defeat Wichita State 57-55 on Saturday night. The loss extends the Shockers' losing streak in Omaha to 13 games dating back to 1992. Wichita State (17-5, 8-3 Missouri Valley Conference) had won four of its first five road games in conference play. After the Shockers missed a shot with 20 seconds left, the Bluejays' Nick Porter grabbed the ball. Creighton guard Johnny Mathies was cut off on his drive to the basket and passed to Tolliver, who swished his shot from the baseline. Trailing by 10 early in the second half, the Bluejays (14-5, 8-3) used a 12-2 run to tie it at 40 with 12:36 to play. They took their first lead since the start of the game with a 7-0 run to make it 51-47 with 6:02 to play. The Shockers regained the lead by scoring five unanswered points. Then Wichita State fell behind by two and the score was tied twice before Tolliver hit the game-winning shot. Brice Nengsu added 10 points for the Bluejays who overcame a horrible start. P.J. Couisnard scored 17 points, Matt Braeuer 12 and Karon Bradley 10 for the Shockers. After giving up the game's first two points, the Shockers built a 23-5 lead 9:15 into the game. Wichita State's first three field goals were 3-pointers, two by Braeuer and one by Kyle Wilson. Both teams went scoreless for more than four minutes with the score at 25-6. Then Creighton scored seven unanswered points in 61 seconds to close within 12 with 4:45 left. The Bluejays made eight free throws in the final 3:46 to make it 30-23 at halftime. The Shockers shot 39 percent (11-28) in the first half. But Creighton made only 21 percent (6-29) of its shots in the half. Creighton finished the game at 33 percent (18-54) and Wichita State shot 42 percent (20-48). But the Shockers hurt themselves with 17 turnovers. The Bluejays committed nine turnovers. The announced crowd of 15,678 set a Creighton record and is the largest ever at a basketball game in Nebraska.
